\begin_layout Subsection
Set-valued Probability Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of using every point in the real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 we can partition the interval into disjoint sets and only consider probability measures up to set membership. The simplest such situation is to partition the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

 (which we will call 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs$
\end_inset

) and the half-open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1]$
\end_inset

 (which we will call 
\begin_inset Formula $\poss$
\end_inset

). The addition that was used to aggregate probabilities is now abstracted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x \vee y=\imposs$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=\imposs$
\end_inset

. We will call the resulting set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \imposs, \poss\right\}$
\end_inset

 together with the with associated operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

. The definition of a probability measure in this case is modified to a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas : \events \rightarrow \mathscr{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\Omega) = \poss$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $E_i$
\end_inset

 of pairwise disjoint events, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\bigcup_i
E_i) = \bigvee_i \pmeas(E_i)$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

