 Under the new set-valued requirement, the probability measure in the first example becomes: 
\begin_inset Formula \[\begin{array}{c@{\qquad\qquad}c}
\begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\emptyset) &=& \imposs \\
\pmeas(\{ HH \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{ HT \}) &=& \imposs \\
\pmeas(\{ TH \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{ TT \}) &=& \imposs \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, HT \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, TH \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH , TT \}) &=& \poss \\
\end{array} & \begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\{  HT, TH \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HT , TT \}) &=& \imposs \\
\pmeas(\{  TH , TT \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, HT, TH \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, HT, TT \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, TH, TT \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HT, TH, TT \}) &=& \poss \\
\pmeas(\{  HH, HT, TH, TT \}) &=& \poss 
\end{array}
\end{array}\]
\end_inset

Despite the fact that we have lost all numeric information, the probability measure still reveals that the second coin is double-headed. We have however lost the information regarding the bias in the first coin. This information can be recovered with a more refined probability measure as we show next. 
